  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "An ode is a poem of sustained address and praise — a formal poem that speaks to a subject (a person, an object, an abstraction, a season) with seriousness, intensity, and often elevation. The ode tradition descends from the Greek poet Pindar (choral odes celebrating athletic victories) through Horace (meditative, personal odes) to the English Romantics, who made the ode a vehicle for philosophical reflection.\nKeats\u0026rsquo;s odes — \u0026ldquo;Ode to a Nightingale,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;Ode on a Grecian Urn,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;To Autumn\u0026rdquo; — exemplify the form\u0026rsquo;s capacity: the speaker addresses a specific thing and, through sustained attention, discovers what it means. The ode\u0026rsquo;s characteristic movement is from observation to meditation to insight (or to the recognition that insight is elusive).\n",
